{
  "id": "019d286c-c8e3-7462-a4e5-9f356aca5e4f",
  "content": "Resolve threw \"GPU memory is full\" with black playback. Claude initially diagnosed it as an out-of-memory issue and we started building a proxy pipeline to work around it. But something didn't add up. I dug deeper and steered us back to the debug logs.</p>\n<p>Turns out it wasn't a memory problem at all. It was a Wayland compatibility issue. Together we landed on three environment variables to force Resolve onto X11 instead. Full 4K playback. No proxies needed.</p>\n\n<p>That's the part people miss about working with AI. It's not \"ask and receive.\" It's a collaboration. Claude brings speed and breadth. You bring judgment and direction. Neither of us would have solved that one alone.</p>\n\n<p>And now I'm thinking bigger. I have a diving trip coming up. Hours of underwater footage from the DJI Action 4 and Insta360 X5. I love editing, but the repetitive parts eat time I'd rather spend diving. I recently found a DaVinci Resolve MCP, and I'm starting to imagine what's possible when an AI can actually interact with your editing timeline. Still brainstorming, but the pieces are coming together.</p>\n\n<p>The stack I built for engineering is now running a full creative workflow. No new hardware. Just the right tools.</p>\n\n<p>Anyone else using AI to streamline their video editing workflow? Curious what people have landed on.</p>\n</div>\n\n</body>\n</html>\n",
